EXT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

A steel warehouse the size of a football field, dark, weeds in the
gravel apron. A sign on the gate: CLOSED BY ORDER — COUNTY REVENUE
RECOVERY. Under it, smaller: NO SALVAGE VALUE.

Mack's truck, then Cricket's, then two more, lights off, roll around
to the loading side.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Flashlights. Mack finds the panel and throws breakers one at a time.
Sodium lamps bang on, row by row, until the whole dead acreage of
the place stands lit: empty auction floor, intact gantry crane,
scale pit, loading docks.

The four olds stand in the middle of it, turning slowly.

DUTCH:
Three-phase power. Sixty-foot clear span. A certified scale.

MACK:
County shut it down for back taxes and forgot it exists. I rent it
through a feed cooperative that doesn't exist either.

A knock at the man-door — two, then two. Mack opens it.

JOSS REED, 26, hoodie, work boots, a duffel. Behind him, TITO,
toolbox in hand, hood under his arm.

JOSS:
Okay so Mack says be here at ten and bring nothing with a battery,
which is like — literally everything is a battery — so I brought
Tito.

GUNNY:
Son. Phones.

Gunny holds out a coffee can. Joss looks at it. Looks at the four
old men looking at him. Drops his phone in. Tito's follows.

MACK:
(to the room)
Joss runs the dock crew days. Fastest hands at Frontier and no
badge access to anything that matters, which makes him invisible.
Tito you know by his work.

Mack nods to Dutch. Dutch opens the binder on a plywood table and
unrolls a pencil drawing over it: a crate, in section. Dimensions,
purge lines, a battery bus. And inside the crate outline, drawn
faint but unmistakable: the profile of a reclined man.

The kids look at it a long moment. Joss's grin goes away.

JOSS:
That's a person. This is a bit, right? Tell me the — this is not a
bit. Okay. Wow. Whose felony is this exactly?

MACK:
Nobody's, if it's done right. Yours to walk away from, right now,
no hard feelings and no second chance.

Tito hasn't looked up from the drawing. He rotates it with one
finger, frowning.

TITO:
This corner joint. You spec'd a fillet here?

DUTCH:
Full-penetration bevel. Page two.

TITO:
(turning the page)
Okay. Okay, yeah. But your purge line comes through two inches from
the weld. Heat's going to cook your fitting. Move it here, come in
under the frame rail, nobody ever sees it.

Dutch looks at the drawing. Looks at Tito. Takes out a pencil and
hands it to him.

Tito takes it, bends over the sheet, and starts drawing the new
line.

JOSS:
(to Mack)
And me? I load boxes.

CRICKET:
You grew up on CB. Mack says your daddy ran freight and kept a rig
in the truck.

JOSS:
Yeah. So?

CRICKET:
So you're mission control.

Joss looks at Cricket a second, then at his own duffel, then back up.

JOSS:
I'll need a better antenna than what I got. And you're going to
want a schedule — a real one, like a net schedule — okay, yeah,
I'm in, obviously I'm in.

MACK:
Comms discipline. That's the whole game, so hear it once. Nothing
electronic. No phones, no email, no cloud, nothing with a battery
you didn't build yourself.

JOSS:
Then how do two hundred guys coordinate a—

DUTCH:
Handwritten letters. Ham net on schedule. A book cipher out of the
Reader's Digest — Cricket has the year and the month.

JOSS:
That's insane. That's like — that's Revolutionary War stuff.

GUNNY:
They've got every algorithm ever written. We've got Valley Forge.

Joss opens his mouth. Closes it.

LATER

Tito, on his knees on the concrete, chalks a full-size crate
outline on the floor off Dutch's dimensions — a long rectangle,
corners squared off a framing square.

The men stand around it, looking down.

Stitch steps over the chalk line, lies down inside it, and sets his
hat on his chest.

STITCH:
Snug.

CUT TO:
